  "prompt": "Why have so many professional wrestlers died young?",
  "response": "The early deaths of many professional wrestlers can be attributed to a combination of factors:\n\n1. **Physical Demands of the Profession**: Wrestling is highly physical and can lead to significant injuries, including concussions, joint problems, and chronic pain. The toll this takes on the body can shorten lifespans, especially when sustained over lengthy careers.\n\n2. **Substance Use**: Many wrestlers have historically used substances such as steroids, painkillers, and other drugs to cope with injuries, enhance performance, or manage the physical demands of the sport. This can lead to various health issues, including heart disease and overdose.\n\n3. **Mental Health Issues**: The pressures of fame, the instability of the wrestling industry, and the physical toll can contribute to mental health issues. Some wrestlers have faced depression and anxiety, which, when left unaddressed, can lead to tragic outcomes.\n\n4. **Lifestyle Factors**: The often erratic schedules, travel, and nightlife associated with professional wrestling can lead to unhealthy lifestyles, including poor diet, lack of sleep, and high-stress levels, which can negatively impact health.\n\n5. **Chronic Health Issues**: Many wrestlers experience chronic health problems resulting from their careers, including cardiovascular disease, liver damage, and other ailments that can dramatically affect longevity.\n\n6. **Tragic Incidents**: In some cases, accidents or unexpected medical emergencies contribute to early deaths.\n\nAlthough awareness of these issues has increased and some organizations have implemented wellness programs, the factors contributing to the early deaths of wrestlers remain a serious concern within the industry.",
